{
  "format": "wspradar.config",
  "schema_version": 1,
  "profile": {
    "id": "zander_tx_buddy_experiment_b",
    "title": {
      "en": "Dr. Zander et al. TX Antenna Comparison: T2FD vs Inverted-V Dipole"
    },
    "description": {
      "en": "[Publication: Zander, J. (2022). Simple HF antenna efficiency comparisons using the WSPR system](https://arxiv.org/abs/2209.08989)\n\nRe-examines Experiment B Figure 5 by pairing SK0WE/B’s 25 m Diamond WD-330 T2FD with SK0WE’s half-wave inverted-V at the same remote receiver and in the same WSPR cycle. In TX Compare → Segment Insight, compare Figure 5 with the right-hand Joint-Spot ΔSNR histogram—not the middle Station Medians histogram. WSPRadar’s finer 1 dB percent bins split the paper’s coarser density bins, making the same strongly negative distribution look more finely structured; aligning the bins reconciles the histogram shape. The current demo contains 140 joint reports across 24 receivers, with mean ΔSNR −9.14 dB, median −9.0 dB and sample σ = 2.99 dB—close to the paper’s −8.4 dB mean and 2.8 dB spread, though not numerically identical. Both analyses show a large disadvantage for the T2FD over the sampled paths."
    }
  },
